ntuition
Approach

First, I sort the array so that all duplicate elements are placed together.
I use backtracking to generate all possible subsets.
For every element, I have two choices:
Include the current element in the subset.
Exclude the current element.
While excluding an element, I skip all of its consecutive duplicates. This ensures that duplicate subsets are never generated.
Every time I reach the end of the array, the current subset is complete, so I add a copy of it to the answer.

Complexity
Time complexity:
There are at most 2^n possible subsets.
Each subset takes O(n) time to copy into the result.
Therefore, the overall time complexity is:
O(n × 2^n)

Space complexity:
The recursion stack can go up to n levels.
The temporary subset (diary) also stores at most n elements.
Ignoring the output array, the auxiliary space complexity is:

O(n)

Including the output, the total space is:

O(n × 2^n)

Code
class Solution:
    def subsetsWithDup(self, nums: List[int]) -> List[List[int]]:
        nums.sort()
        result , diary , n = [] , [] , len(nums)
        def fun(i):
            if i == n:
                result.append(diary.copy())
                return
            diary.append(nums[i])
            fun(i+1)
            diary.pop()
            idx = i + 1
            while idx < n and nums[idx] == nums[idx - 1]:
                idx += 1
            fun(idx)
            return
        fun(0)
        return result
